If one holds oneself dear, one should diligently
watch oneself. Let the wise man keep vigil during
any of the three watches of the night.

			 Dhammapada - 157
%
One should first establish oneself in what is
proper; then only should one instruct others. Thus
the wise man will not be reproached.

			 Dhammapada - 158
%
One should do what one teaches others to do; if
one would train others, one should be well
controlled oneself. Difficult, indeed, is self-
control.

			 Dhammapada - 159
%
One truly is the protector of oneself; who else
could the protector be? With oneself fully
controlled, one gains a mastery that is hard to
gain.

			 Dhammapada - 160
%
The evil a witless man does by himself, born of
himself and produced by himself, grinds him as a
diamond grinds a hard gem.

			 Dhammapada - 161
%
Just as a single creeper strangles the tree on
which it grows, even so, a man who is exceedingly
depraved harms himself as only an enemy might
wish.

			 Dhammapada - 162
%
Easy to do are things that are bad and harmful to
oneself. But exceedingly difficult to do are
things that are good and beneficial.

			 Dhammapada - 163
%
Whoever, on account of perverted views, scorns the
Teaching of the Perfected Ones, the Noble and
Righteous Ones—that fool, like the bamboo,
produces fruits only for self destruction.

			 Dhammapada - 164
%
By oneself is evil done; by oneself is one
defiled. By oneself is evil left undone; by
oneself is one made pure. Purity and impurity
depend on oneself; no one can purify another.

			 Dhammapada - 165
%
Let one not neglect one’s own welfare for the sake
of another, however great. Clearly understanding
one’s own welfare, let one be intent upon the
good.

			 Dhammapada - 166
%
Follow not the vulgar way; live not in
heedlessness; hold not false views; linger not
long in worldly existence.

			 Dhammapada - 167
%
Arise! Do not be heedless! Lead a righteous life.
The righteous live happily both in this world and
the next.

			 Dhammapada - 168
%
Lead a righteous life; lead not a base life. The
righteous live happily both in this world and the
next.

			 Dhammapada - 169
%
One who looks upon the world as a bubble and a
mirage, him the King of Death sees not.

			 Dhammapada - 170
%
Come! Behold this world, which is like a decorated
royal chariot. Here fools flounder, but the wise
have no attachment to it.

			 Dhammapada - 171
%
He who having been heedless is heedless no more,
illuminates this world like the moon freed from
clouds.

			 Dhammapada - 172
%
He, who by good deeds covers the evil he has done,
illuminates this world like the moon freed from
clouds.

			 Dhammapada - 173
%
Blind is the world; here only a few possess
insight. Only a few, like birds escaping from the
net, go to realms of bliss.

			 Dhammapada - 174
%
Swans fly on the path of the sun; men pass through
the air by psychic powers; the wise are led away
from the world after vanquishing Mara and his
host.

			 Dhammapada - 175
%
For a liar who has violated the one law (of
truthfulness) who holds in scorn the hereafter,
there is no evil that he cannot do.

			 Dhammapada - 176
%
Truly, misers fare not to heavenly realms; nor,
indeed, do fools praise generosity. But the wise
man rejoices in giving, and by that alone does he
become happy hereafter.

			 Dhammapada - 177
%
Better than sole sovereignty over the earth,
better than going to heaven, better even than
lordship over all the worlds is the supramundane
Fruition of Stream Entrance.

			 Dhammapada - 178
%
By what track can you trace that trackless Buddha
of limitless range, whose victory nothing can
undo, whom none of the vanquished defilements can
ever pursue?

			 Dhammapada - 179
%
By what track can you trace that trackless Buddha
of limitless range, in whom exists no longer, the
entangling and embroiling craving that perpetuates
becoming?

			 Dhammapada - 180
%
Those wise ones who are devoted to meditation and
who delight in the calm of renunciation—such
mindful ones, Supreme Buddhas, even the gods hold
dear.

			 Dhammapada - 181
%
Hard is it to be born a man; hard is the life of
mortals. Hard is it to gain the opportunity of
hearing the Sublime Truth, and hard to encounter
is the arising of the Buddhas.

			 Dhammapada - 182
%
To avoid all evil, to cultivate good, and to
cleanse one’s mind—this is the teaching of the
Buddhas.

			 Dhammapada - 183
%
Enduring patience is the highest austerity.
“Nibbana is supreme,” say the Buddhas. He is not a
true monk who harms another, nor a true renunciate
who oppresses others.

			 Dhammapada - 184
%
Not despising, not harming, restraint according to
the code of monastic discipline, moderation in
food, dwelling in solitude, devotion to
meditation—this is the teaching of the Buddhas.

			 Dhammapada - 185
%
SC 187There is no satisfying sensual desires, even
with the rain of gold coins. For sensual pleasures
give little satisfaction and much pain. Having
understood this, the wise man finds no delight
even in heavenly pleasures. The disciple of the
Supreme Buddha delights in the destruction of
craving.

			 Dhammapada - 186
%
Driven only by fear, do men go for refuge to many
places—to hills, woods, groves, trees and shrines.

			 Dhammapada - 188
%
Such, indeed, is no safe refuge; such is not the
refuge supreme. Not by resorting to such a refuge
is one released from all suffering.

			 Dhammapada - 189
%
SC 191He who has gone for refuge to the Buddha,
the Teaching and his Order, penetrates with
transcendental wisdom the Four Noble
Truths—suffering, the cause of suffering, the
cessation of suffering, and the Noble Eightfold
Path leading to the cessation of suffering.

			 Dhammapada - 190
%
This indeed is the safe refuge, this the refuge
supreme. Having gone to such a refuge, one is
released from all suffering.

			 Dhammapada - 192
%
Hard to find is the thoroughbred man (the Buddha);
he is not born everywhere. Where such a wise man
is born, that clan thrives happily.

			 Dhammapada - 193
%
Blessed is the birth of the Buddhas; blessed is
the enunciation of the sacred Teaching; blessed is
the harmony in the Order, and blessed is the
spiritual pursuit of the united truth-seeker.

			 Dhammapada - 194
%
SC 196He who reveres those worthy of reverence,
the Buddhas and their disciples, who have
transcended all obstacles and passed beyond the
reach of sorrow and lamentation—he who reveres
such peaceful and fearless ones, his merit none
can compute by any measure.

			 Dhammapada - 195
%
Happy indeed we live, friendly amidst the hostile.
Amidst hostile men we dwell free from hatred.

			 Dhammapada - 197
%
Happy indeed we live, friendly amidst the
afflicted (by craving). Amidst afflicted men we
dwell free from affliction.

			 Dhammapada - 198
%
Happy indeed we live, free from avarice amidst the
avaricious. Amidst the avaricious men we dwell
free from avarice.

			 Dhammapada - 199
%
Happy indeed we live, we who possess nothing.
Feeders on joy we shall be, like the Radiant Gods.

			 Dhammapada - 200
%
Victory begets enmity; the defeated dwell in pain.
Happily the peaceful live, discarding both victory
and defeat.

			 Dhammapada - 201
%
There is no fire like lust and no crime like
hatred. There is no ill like the aggregates (of
existence) and no bliss higher than the peace (of
Nibbana).

			 Dhammapada - 202
%
Hunger is the worst disease, conditioned things
the worst suffering. Knowing this as it really is,
the wise realize Nibbana, the highest bliss.

			 Dhammapada - 203
%
Health is the most precious gain and contentment
the greatest wealth. A trustworthy person is the
best kinsman, Nibbana the highest bliss.

			 Dhammapada - 204
%
Having savored the taste of solitude and peace (of
Nibbana), pain-free and stainless he becomes,
drinking deep the taste of the bliss of the Truth.

			 Dhammapada - 205
%
Good is it to see the Noble Ones; to live with
them is ever blissful. One will always be happy by
not encountering fools.

			 Dhammapada - 206
%
Indeed, he who moves in the company of fools
grieves for longing. Association with fools is
ever painful, like partnership with an enemy. But
association with the wise is happy, like meeting
one’s own kinsmen.

			 Dhammapada - 207
%
Therefore, follow the Noble One, who is steadfast,
wise, learned, dutiful and devout. One should
follow only such a man, who is truly good and
discerning, even as the moon follows the path of
the stars.

			 Dhammapada - 208
%
Giving himself to things to be shunned and not
exerting where exertion is needed, a seeker after
pleasures, having given up his true welfare,
envies those intent upon theirs.

			 Dhammapada - 209
%
Seek no intimacy with the beloved and also not
with the unloved, for not to see the beloved and
to see the unloved, both are painful.

			 Dhammapada - 210
%
Therefore hold nothing dear, for separation from
the dear is painful. There are no bonds for those
who have nothing beloved or unloved.

			 Dhammapada - 211
%
From endearment springs grief, from endearment
springs fear. For one who is wholly free from
endearment there is no grief, whence then fear?

			 Dhammapada - 212
%
From affection springs grief, from affection
springs fear. For one who is wholly free from
affection there is no grief, whence then fear?

			 Dhammapada - 213
%
From attachment springs grief, from attachment
springs fear. For one who is wholly free from
attachment there is no grief, whence then fear?

			 Dhammapada - 214
%
From lust springs grief, from lust springs fear.
For one who is wholly free from craving there is
no grief; whence then fear?

			 Dhammapada - 215
%
From craving springs grief, from craving springs
fear. For one who is wholly free from craving
there is no grief; whence then fear?

			 Dhammapada - 216
%
People hold dear him who embodies virtue and
insight, who is principled, has realized the
truth, and who himself does what he ought to be
doing.

			 Dhammapada - 217
%
One who is intent upon the Ineffable (Nibbana),
dwells with mind inspired (by supramundane
wisdom), and is no more bound by sense
pleasures—such a man is called “One Bound
