			 Dhammapada - 218
%
When, after a long absence, a man safely returns
from afar, his relatives, friends and well-wishers
welcome him home on arrival.

			 Dhammapada - 219
%
As kinsmen welcome a dear one on arrival, even so
his own good deeds will welcome the doer of good
who has gone from this world to the next.

			 Dhammapada - 220
%
One should give up anger, renounce pride, and
overcome all fetters. Suffering never befalls him
who clings not to mind and body and is detached.

			 Dhammapada - 221
%
He who checks rising anger as a charioteer checks
a rolling chariot, him I call a true charioteer.
Others only hold the reins.

			 Dhammapada - 222
%
Overcome the angry by non-anger; overcome the
wicked by goodness; overcome the miser by
generosity; overcome the liar by truth.

			 Dhammapada - 223
%
Speak the truth; yield not to anger; when asked,
give even if you only have a little. By these
three means can one reach the presence of the
gods.

			 Dhammapada - 224
%
Those sages who are inoffensive and ever
restrained in body, go to the Deathless State,
where, having gone, they grieve no more.

			 Dhammapada - 225
%
Those who are ever vigilant, who discipline
themselves day and night, and are ever intent upon
Nibbana—their defilements fade away.

			 Dhammapada - 226
%
O Atula! Indeed, this is an ancient practice, not
one only of today: they blame those who remain
silent, they blame those who speak much, they
blame those who speak in moderation. There is none
in the world who is not blamed.

			 Dhammapada - 227
%
There never was, there never will be, nor is there
now, a person who is wholly blamed or wholly
praised.

			 Dhammapada - 228
%
But the man whom the wise praise, after observing
him day after day, is one of flawless character,
wise, and endowed with knowledge and virtue.

			 Dhammapada - 229
%
Who can blame such a one, as worthy as a coin of
refined gold? Even the gods praise him; by Brahma,
too, is he praised.

			 Dhammapada - 230
%
Let a man guard himself against irritability in
bodily action; let him be controlled in deed.
Abandoning bodily misconduct, let him practice
good conduct in deed.

			 Dhammapada - 231
%
Let a man guard himself against irritability in
speech; let him be controlled in speech.
Abandoning verbal misconduct, let him practice
good conduct in speech.

			 Dhammapada - 232
%
Let a man guard himself against irritability in
thought; let him be controlled in mind. Abandoning
mental misconduct, let him practice good conduct
in thought.

			 Dhammapada - 233
%
The wise are controlled in bodily action,
controlled in speech and controlled in thought.
They are truly well-controlled.

			 Dhammapada - 234
%
Like a withered leaf are you now; death’s
messengers await you. You stand on the eve of your
departure, yet you have made no provision for your
journey!

			 Dhammapada - 235
%
Make an island for yourself! Strive hard and
become wise! Rid of impurities and cleansed of
stain, you shall enter the celestial abode of the
Noble Ones.

			 Dhammapada - 236
%
Your life has come to an end now; You are setting
forth into the presence of Yama, the king of
death. No resting place is there for you on the
way, yet you have made no provision for the
journey!

			 Dhammapada - 237
%
Make an island unto yourself! Strive hard and
become wise! Rid of impurities and cleansed of
stain, you shall not come again to birth and
decay.

			 Dhammapada - 238
%
One by one, little by little, moment by moment, a
wise man should remove his own impurities, as a
smith removes his dross from silver.

			 Dhammapada - 239
%
Just as rust arising from iron eats away the base
from which it arises, even so, their own deeds
lead transgressors to states of woe.

			 Dhammapada - 240
%
Non-repetition is the bane of scriptures; neglect
is the bane of a home; slovenliness is the bane of
personal appearance, and heedlessness is the bane
of a guard.

			 Dhammapada - 241
%
Unchastity is the taint in a woman; niggardliness
is the taint in a giver. Taints, indeed, are all
evil things, both in this world and the next.

			 Dhammapada - 242
%
A worse taint than these is ignorance, the worst
of all taints. Destroy this one taint and become
taintless, O monks!

			 Dhammapada - 243
%
Easy is life for the shameless one who is impudent
as a crow, is backbiting and forward, arrogant and
corrupt.

			 Dhammapada - 244
%
Difficult is life for the modest one who always
seeks purity, is detached and unassuming, clean in
life, and discerning.

			 Dhammapada - 245
%
SC 247One who destroys life, utters lies, takes
what is not given, goes to another man’s wife, and
is addicted to intoxicating drinks—such a man digs
up his own root even in this world.

			 Dhammapada - 246
%
Know this, O good man: evil things are difficult
to control. Let not greed and wickedness drag you
to protracted misery.

			 Dhammapada - 248
%
People give according to their faith or regard. If
one becomes discontented with the food and drink
given by others, one does not attain meditative
absorption, either by day or by night.

			 Dhammapada - 249
%
But he in who this (discontent) is fully
destroyed, uprooted and extinct, he attains
absorption, both by day and by night.

			 Dhammapada - 250
%
There is no fire like lust; there is no grip like
hatred; there is no net like delusion; there is no
river like craving.

			 Dhammapada - 251
%
Easily seen is the fault of others, but one’s own
fault is difficult to see. Like chaff one winnows
another’s faults, but hides one’s own, even as a
crafty fowler hides behind sham branches.

			 Dhammapada - 252
%
He who seeks another’s faults, who is ever
censorious—his cankers grow. He is far from
destruction of the cankers.

			 Dhammapada - 253
%
There is no track in the sky, and no recluse
outside (the Buddha’s dispensation). Mankind
delights in worldliness, but the Buddhas are free
from worldliness.

			 Dhammapada - 254
%
There is no track in the sky, and no recluse
outside (the Buddha’s dispensation). There are no
conditioned things that are eternal, and no
instability in the Buddhas.

			 Dhammapada - 255
%
Not by passing arbitrary judgments does a man
become just; a wise man is he who investigates
both right and wrong.

			 Dhammapada - 256
%
He who does not judge others arbitrarily, but
passes judgment impartially according to the
truth, that sagacious man is a guardian of law and
is called just.

			 Dhammapada - 257
%
One is not wise because one speaks much. He who is
peaceable, friendly and fearless is called wise.

			 Dhammapada - 258
%
A man is not versed in Dhamma because he speaks
much. He who, after hearing a little Dhamma,
realizes its truth directly and is not heedless of
it, is truly versed in the Dhamma.

			 Dhammapada - 259
%
A monk is not an elder because his head is gray.
He is but ripe in age, and he is called one grown
old in vain.

			 Dhammapada - 260
%
One in whom there is truthfulness, virtue,
inoffensiveness, restraint and self-mastery, who
is free from defilements and is wise—he is truly
called an Elder.

			 Dhammapada - 261
%
Not by mere eloquence nor by beauty of form does a
man become accomplished, if he is jealous, selfish
and deceitful.

			 Dhammapada - 262
%
But he in whom these are wholly destroyed,
uprooted and extinct, and who has cast out
hatred—that wise man is truly accomplished.

			 Dhammapada - 263
%
Not by shaven head does a man who is indisciplined
and untruthful become a monk. How can he who is
full of desire and greed be a monk?

			 Dhammapada - 264
%
He who wholly subdues evil both small and great is
called a monk, because he has overcome all evil.

			 Dhammapada - 265
%
He is not a monk just because he lives on others’
alms. Not by adopting outward form does one become
a true monk.

			 Dhammapada - 266
%
Whoever here (in the Dispensation) lives a holy
life, transcending both merit and demerit, and
walks with understanding in this world—he is truly
called a monk.

			 Dhammapada - 267
%
Not by observing silence does one become a sage,
if he be foolish and ignorant. But that man is
wise who, as if holding a balance-scale accepts
only the good.

			 Dhammapada - 268
%
The sage (thus) rejecting the evil, is truly a
sage. Since he comprehends both (present and
future) worlds, he is called a sage.

			 Dhammapada - 269
%
He is not noble who injures living beings. He is
called noble because he is harmless towards all
living beings.

			 Dhammapada - 270
%
SC 272Not by rules and observances, not even by
much learning, nor by gain of absorption, nor by a
life of seclusion, nor by thinking, “I enjoy the
bliss of renunciation, which is not experienced by
the worldling” should you, O monks, rest content,
until the utter destruction of cankers
(Arahantship) is reached.

			 Dhammapada - 271
%
Of all the paths the Eightfold Path is the best;
of all the truths the Four Noble Truths are the
best; of all things passionlessness is the best:
of men the Seeing One (the Buddha) is the best.

			 Dhammapada - 273
%
This is the only path; there is none other for the
purification of insight. Tread this path, and you
will bewilder Mara.

			 Dhammapada - 274
%
Walking upon this path you will make an end of
suffering. Having discovered how to pull out the
thorn of lust, I make known the path.

			 Dhammapada - 275
%
You yourselves must strive; the Buddhas only point
the way. Those meditative ones who tread the path
are released from the bonds of Mara.

			 Dhammapada - 276
%
“All conditioned things are impermanent”—when one
sees this with wisdom, one turns away from
suffering. This is the path to purification.

			 Dhammapada - 277
%
“All conditioned things are unsatisfactory”—when
one sees this with wisdom, one turns away from
suffering. This is the path to purification.

			 Dhammapada - 278
%
“All things are not-self”—when one sees this with
wisdom, one turns away from suffering. This is the
path to purification.

			 Dhammapada - 279
%
The idler who does not exert himself when he
should, who though young and strong is full of
sloth, with a mind full of vain thoughts—such an
indolent man does not find the path to wisdom.

			 Dhammapada - 280
%
Let a man be watchful of speech, well controlled
in mind, and not commit evil in bodily action. Let
him purify these three courses of action, and win
the path made known by the Great Sage.

			 Dhammapada - 281
%
Wisdom springs from meditation; without meditation
wisdom wanes. Having known these two paths of
progress and decline, let a man so conduct himself
that his wisdom may increase.

			 Dhammapada - 282
%
Cut down the forest (lust), but not the tree; from
the forest springs fear. Having cut down the
forest and the underbrush (desire), be
passionless, O monks!

			 Dhammapada - 283
%
For so long as the underbrush of desire, even the
most subtle, of a man towards a woman is not cut
down, his mind is in bondage, like the sucking
calf to its mother.

			 Dhammapada - 284
%
Cut off your affection in the manner of a man who
plucks with his hand an autumn lotus. Cultivate
only the path to peace, Nibbana, as made known by
the Exalted One.

			 Dhammapada - 285
%
“Here shall I live during the rains, here in
winter and summer”—thus thinks the fool. He does
not realize the danger (that death might
intervene).

			 Dhammapada - 286
%
As a great flood carries away a sleeping village,
so death seizes and carries away the man with a
clinging mind, doting on his children and cattle.

			 Dhammapada - 287
%
For him who is assailed by death there is no
protection by kinsmen. None there are to save
him—no sons, nor father, nor relatives.

			 Dhammapada - 288
%
Realizing this fact, let the wise man, restrained
by morality, hasten to clear the path leading to
Nibbana.

			 Dhammapada - 289
%
If by renouncing a lesser happiness one may
realize a greater happiness, let the wise man
renounce the lesser, having regard for the
greater.

			 Dhammapada - 290
%
Entangled by the bonds of hate, he who seeks his
own happiness by inflicting pain on others, is
never delivered from hatred.

			 Dhammapada - 291
%
The cankers only increase for those who are
arrogant and heedless, who leave undone what
should be done and do what should not be done.

			 Dhammapada - 292
%
The cankers cease for those mindful and clearly
comprehending ones who always earnestly practice
mindfulness of the body, who do not resort to what
should not be done, and steadfastly pursue what
should be done.

			 Dhammapada - 293
%
Having slain mother (craving), father (self-
conceit), two warrior-kings (eternalism and
nihilism), and destroyed a country (sense organs
and sense objects) together with its treasurer
(attachment and lust), ungrieving goes the holy
man.

			 Dhammapada - 294
%
Having slain mother, father, two brahman kings
(two extreme views), and a tiger as the fifth (the
five mental hindrances), ungrieving goes the holy
man.

			 Dhammapada - 295
%
Those disciples of Gotama ever awaken happily who
day and night constantly practice the Recollection
of the Qualities of the Buddha.

			 Dhammapada - 296
